People's tracking devices are increasingly being asked by parents who want to monitor their children.
The fear of their children leads more and more people to think about monitoring them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars, can also be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases such as that of Little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is now as large as a box of alumettes but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of Little Anicka stirred up a large number of people and they began to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to interfere with their private lives.
"We are trying to tell everyone that this is not a spin-off but only another way to reduce the likelihood that there is another tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I assume there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of a person who is not aware, but I have not yet met such cases."
"Most people are customers who actually buy the product for security reasons, Pilin adds.
According to him, children should always know to what purpose "the box" is used and how to use it in case of emergency.
The child psychologist Dana Bockova draws attention to the fact that if the child does not want to wear such a thing on him, he will get rid of it.
"And even smaller ones can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something when they don't want to be under control."
"The portable phones, which can be cut like these tracking devices, have already brought the parents to long waiting," says Bockova.
According to it, the fact that this type of device can help in the event of aggression is very controversial.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate him."
"Now it's the phone."
"As soon as tracking devices develop, they (criminals) will also search for them because the sale will be supported by a advertising campaign."
"In such cases criminals will always be in advance on the police," says the psychologist.
She confesses as well as such devices can help during an unprepared aggression by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of the RC Monitoring company, which offers tracking services for both cars and for people, claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an aggression.
"The device may be set in such a way as to be in regular emissions after a specified period."
"In the case where the device is destroyed, the last position of the person concerned remains."
'The most expensive devices also have a tiltimeter that immediately signals the position of the person who slides and finds himself in a position lengthened without moving,' says Cech.
According to him, portable smartphones that are equipped with a navigation system can offer a comparable service after they have formed it with a special proological.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is a device similar to that which is carried depending on the size of an alumina box or the smallest telephones.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of the company Macro Weil, that is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the possible aggressor will not recognize the tracking device."
"Or he will report it after some time, which will give the police a little more time," he adds.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
This is a combination of GPS position acquisition systems (which is commonly used in self-navigation) and a function of a mobile phone that alerts the current position of a vehicle.
