A Global Plan to Renewal of Light
The United Nations proposed yesterday in Cancún a plan for the renovation of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas reduction (GES) that corresponds almost to the third of the additional reduction to be achieved in order to stabilise the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the United Nations hopes to adopt in Cancún in order to compensate for the absence of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan filed yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that monopolies still from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluo-compact bulbs or, better, by electroluminescent diode (DEL or "LED") bulbs, the essence of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GES emitted on the planet would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen, last year, large emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should lead to global GES emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will have to be subtracted from this budget by 5 Gt in order to stabilise the rise in the climate by 2020 at 2 centigrades in order to avoid becoming out of control.
In the incandescent ampoules, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, that is, 5%, is produced from light.
With fluo-compact ampoules, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new ampoules in DEL, this need for energy is reduced twice again.
Fluo-compact ampoules average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new bulbs in DEL, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company also participated in the study of the United Nations - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, giving an idea of the economy possible with a replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
All these new ampoules can also work with reestates as well as very little heat.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown reservations instead of fluo-compact ampoules because they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact ampoule, but rather the thermal power plants in coal, which emit a lot of mercury to produce spent electricity in incandescent ampoules.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report details the gains that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, or the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
